## Description {#details}

This file builds on the <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/adt/graphtraits-h">ADT/GraphTraits.h</a> file to build a generic graph post order iterator.

This should work over any graph type that has a GraphTraits specialization.

<Link id="l00031" /><CodeLine lineNumber="31"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The po&#95;iterator&#95;storage template provides access to the set of already</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00032" /><CodeLine lineNumber="32"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// visited nodes during the po&#95;iterator&#39;s depth-first traversal.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00033" /><CodeLine lineNumber="33"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00034" /><CodeLine lineNumber="34"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The default implementation simply contains a set of visited nodes, while</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00035" /><CodeLine lineNumber="35"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// the External=true version uses a reference to an external set.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00036" /><CodeLine lineNumber="36"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00037" /><CodeLine lineNumber="37"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// It is possible to prune the depth-first traversal in several ways:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00038" /><CodeLine lineNumber="38"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00039" /><CodeLine lineNumber="39"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - When providing an external set that already contains some graph nodes,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00040" /><CodeLine lineNumber="40"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   those nodes won&#39;t be visited again. This is useful for restarting a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00041" /><CodeLine lineNumber="41"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   post-order traversal on a graph with nodes that aren&#39;t dominated by a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00042" /><CodeLine lineNumber="42"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   single node.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00043" /><CodeLine lineNumber="43"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00044" /><CodeLine lineNumber="44"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - By providing a custom SetType class, unwanted graph nodes can be excluded</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00045" /><CodeLine lineNumber="45"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   by having the insert() function return false. This could for example</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00046" /><CodeLine lineNumber="46"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   confine a CFG traversal to blocks in a specific loop.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00047" /><CodeLine lineNumber="47"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00048" /><CodeLine lineNumber="48"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// - Finally, by specializing the po&#95;iterator&#95;storage template itself, graph</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00049" /><CodeLine lineNumber="49"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   edges can be pruned by returning false in the insertEdge() function. This</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00050" /><CodeLine lineNumber="50"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   could be used to remove loop back-edges from the CFG seen by po&#95;iterator.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00051" /><CodeLine lineNumber="51"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00052" /><CodeLine lineNumber="52"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// A specialized po&#95;iterator&#95;storage class can observe both the pre-order and</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00053" /><CodeLine lineNumber="53"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// the post-order. The insertEdge() function is called in a pre-order, while</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00054" /><CodeLine lineNumber="54"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// the finishPostorder() function is called just before the po&#95;iterator moves</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00055" /><CodeLine lineNumber="55"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// on to the next node.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00056" /><CodeLine lineNumber="56"></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00271" /><CodeLine lineNumber="271"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//===--------------------------------------------------------------------===//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00272" /><CodeLine lineNumber="272"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Reverse Post Order CFG iterator code</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00273" /><CodeLine lineNumber="273"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//===--------------------------------------------------------------------===//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00274" /><CodeLine lineNumber="274"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00275" /><CodeLine lineNumber="275"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// This is used to visit basic blocks in a method in reverse post order.  This</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00276" /><CodeLine lineNumber="276"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// class is awkward to use because I don&#39;t know a good incremental algorithm to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00277" /><CodeLine lineNumber="277"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// computer RPO from a graph.  Because of this, the construction of the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00278" /><CodeLine lineNumber="278"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// ReversePostOrderTraversal object is expensive (it must walk the entire graph</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00279" /><CodeLine lineNumber="279"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// with a postorder iterator to build the data structures).  The moral of this</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00280" /><CodeLine lineNumber="280"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// story is: Don&#39;t create more ReversePostOrderTraversal classes than necessary.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00281" /><CodeLine lineNumber="281"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00282" /><CodeLine lineNumber="282"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Because it does the traversal in its constructor, it won&#39;t invalidate when</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00283" /><CodeLine lineNumber="283"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// BasicBlocks are removed, &#42;but&#42; it may contain erased blocks. Some places</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00284" /><CodeLine lineNumber="284"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// rely on this behavior (i.e. GVN).</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00285" /><CodeLine lineNumber="285"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00286" /><CodeLine lineNumber="286"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// This class should be used like this:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00287" /><CodeLine lineNumber="287"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00288" /><CodeLine lineNumber="288"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   ReversePostOrderTraversal&lt;Function&#42;&gt; RPOT(FuncPtr); // Expensive to create</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00289" /><CodeLine lineNumber="289"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   for (rpo&#95;iterator I = RPOT.begin(); I != RPOT.end(); ++I) &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00290" /><CodeLine lineNumber="290"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//      ...</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00291" /><CodeLine lineNumber="291"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   &#125;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00292" /><CodeLine lineNumber="292"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   for (rpo&#95;iterator I = RPOT.begin(); I != RPOT.end(); ++I) &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00293" /><CodeLine lineNumber="293"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//      ...</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00294" /><CodeLine lineNumber="294"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   &#125;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00295" /><CodeLine lineNumber="295"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// &#125;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00296" /><CodeLine lineNumber="296"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00297" /><CodeLine lineNumber="297"></CodeLine>
